<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the foundational `x_casemgmt_case`
    custom table inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    This table is the case-lifecycle anchor of the POC. It replaces the case-domain
    subset of ArkCase's `acm_case_file` MySQL table (the JPA entity `CaseFile`
    in acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/com/
    armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java) - converting the JPA
    @Entity / @Table(name="acm_case_file") / @Inheritance(SINGLE_TABLE) pattern
    into a ServiceNow scoped table whose discriminator collapses into a `type`
    Choice rather than a class-name discriminator column.

    This record authors ONLY table-level metadata (name, labels, parent class,
    scope linkage, auto-numbering reference, and access flags). The 14 fields
    on this table (number, type, status, priority, subject, description,
    opened_date, closed_date, assigned_group, assigned_agent, requester_name,
    requester_email — the 12 AAP-enumerated user-prompt fields — plus the
    internal pending_reason choice and the virtual duration_to_close Function
    Field) are authored as sys_dictionary records in the sibling
    ../dictionary/ folder. The platform automatically inherits the standard
    sys_* audit columns (sys_id,
    sys_created_on, sys_created_by, sys_updated_on, sys_updated_by) by virtue
    of being a sys_db_object record.

    Constraints honored:
      - Scoped-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into the
        x_casemgmt scope; no global-scope writes.
      - Zero hardcoded sys_id literals in any reference field; sys_scope,
        sys_package, and number_ref all resolve by scope name via the `source`
        attribute. The sys_id element below is THIS record's own primary key
        (deterministic MD5 of the table name) and is not a reference to any
        other record.
      - super_class is empty: this table extends NOTHING. It does not extend
        the OOB `task` table (which would write to global scope and violate
        AAP Section 0.3.2). The platform still provides standard sys_* audit columns
        because sys_db_object records always do.
      - create_access_controls is false: ServiceNow auto-creates a default ACL
        set when this is true. Since ../acl/ enumerates a precise role x table
        x CRUD matrix with custom "Assigned only" conditions for case_agent,
        the auto-generated ACLs would conflict and are explicitly suppressed
        here.
      - The concrete scope identifier casemgmt is used throughout per AAP convention; ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the scope id is concrete in the XML before export.
-->
<record_update table="sys_db_object">
    <sys_db_object action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <access>public</access>
        <actions_update>true</actions_update>
        <alter_access>public</alter_access>
